&hellip;</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">O</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&theta;</mml:mi><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace></mml:mrow></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow></mml:mfenced></mml:math><span class="equ">E30</span></div><p id="p53">And we let <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m233"><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&psi;</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mfenced open="(" close=")"><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">i</mml:mi></mml:mfenced></mml:math></span>to be a vector that stores the arguments that maximize <a href="#E30" class="ref-link" data-ref-style="disp-formula">Eq. (30)</a>, we can write Viterbi algorithm to solve the problem mentioned in subsection (3.1) as follows:</p><p id="p54">1) step 1 initializes <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m234"><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&delta;</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mfenced open="(" close=")"><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">i</mml:mi></mml:mfenced></mml:math></span>and <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m235"><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&psi;</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mfenced open="(" close=")"><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">i</mml:mi></mml:mfenced></mml:math></span>.</p><div id="df_" class="formula panel"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" specific-use="web-only" id="m236"><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&delta;</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mfenced open="(" close=")"><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">i</mml:mi></mml:mfenced><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&pi;</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvari