/mml:math><span class="equ">E36</span></div><p id="p59">We also define <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m257"><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&zeta;</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mfenced open="(" close=")" separators=","><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">i</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">j</mml:mi></mml:mfenced></mml:math></span>to be the probability of being in state <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m258"><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">s</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math></span>at time <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m259"><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:math></span>and transiting to state <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m260"><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">s</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">j</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math></span>at time <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m261"><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo></mml:math></span>given <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m262"><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">O</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math></span>,<span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m263"><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mn>2</mml:mn><mml:mo>&hellip;</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">L</mml:mi></mml:math></span>. <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m264"><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&zeta;</mml:mi><mml: