abilities. By setting the initial values as given in [<a href="#B19" class="ref-link" data-ref-style="bibr">19</a>] assuming the Markov chain is presumed to be ergodic:</p><div id="df_" class="formula panel"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" specific-use="web-only" id="m379"><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">P</mml:mi><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:mi>(</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">s</mml:mi><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">i</mml:mi><mml:mfenced open="|" close=")"><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&psi;</mml:mi><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub></mml:mfenced><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">P</mml:mi><mml:mi>jj</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn><mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">P</mml:mi><mml:mi>ii</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">P</mml:mi><mml:mi>jj</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac></mml:math><span class="equ"></span></div><p>we can iterate the <a href="#E49" class="ref-link" data-ref-style="disp-formula">Eqs. (49)</a> and <a href="#E50" class="ref-link" data-ref-style="disp-formula">(50)</a> to obtain the filtering probabilities <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m380"><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">P</mml:mi><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:mi>(</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">s</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">i</mml:mi><mml:mfenced open="|" close=")" separators=";"><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&psi;</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&theta;</mml:mi></mml:mfenced></mml:math></span> and the conditional densities <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m381"><mml:mi mathvariant="script">F</mml:mi><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:mfenced open="(" close=")" separators="|;"><mml:mrow><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">z</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">s</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&psi;</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi><mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&theta;</mml:mi></mml:mfenced></mml:math></span> for <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m382"><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mn>2</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>&hellip;</mml:mo><mml:mo>.</mml:mo><mml:mo>.</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">T</mml:mi></mml:math></span>. Then we can compute the logarithmic likelihood function using</p><div id="df_E51" class="formula panel"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" specific-use="web-only" id="m383"><mml:mtext>log</mml:mtext><mml:mfenced open="(" close=")"><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">L</mml:mi><mml:mfenced open="(" close=")"><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&theta;</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">&#770;</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow></mml:mfenced><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:munderover><mml:mo>&sum;</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">T</mml:mi></mml:munderover><mml:munderover><mml:mo>&sum;</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">i</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:munderover><mml:mtext>log</mml:mtext><mml:mi>(</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="script">F</mml:mi><mml:mfenced open="(" close=")"><mml:mrow><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Z</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mfenced open="|" close=")" separators=",;"><mml:mrow><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">S</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">i</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&psi;</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi><mml:mo>&minus;</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&theta;</mml:mi></mml:mfenced><mml:mo>&times;</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">P</mml:mi><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:mfenced open="(" close=")" separators="|;"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">S</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">i</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&psi;</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&theta;</mml:mi></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow></mml:mfenced></mml:math><span class="equ">E51</span></div><p>where <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m384"><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">L</mml:mi><mml:mfenced open="(" close=")"><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&theta;</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">&#770;</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:mfenced></mml:math></span> is the maximized value of the likelihood function. The model estimation can finally be obtained by finding the set of parameters <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m385"><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&theta;</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">&#770;</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:math></span> that maximize the <a href="#E51" class="ref-link" data-ref-style="disp-formula">Eq. (51)</a> using numerical-search algorithm. The estimated filtering and prediction probabilities can then be easily calculated by plugging <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m386"><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&theta;</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="true">&#770;</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:math></span> into the equation formulae of these probabilities. We adopt the approximation in Ref [<a href="#B20" class="ref-link" data-ref-style="bibr">20</a>] for computing the smoothing probabilities <span class="inline-formula"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="m387"><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">P</mml:mi><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:mi>(</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">s</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">i</mml:mi><mml:mfenced open="|" close=")" separators=";"><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&psi;</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">L</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&theta;</mml:mi></mml:mfenced></mml:math></span></p><div id="df_" class="formula panel"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" specific-use="web-only" id="m388"><mml:mspace width="0.75em"></mml:mspace><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">P</mml:mi><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:mi>(</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">s</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">i</mml:mi><mml:mfenced open="|" close=")" separators=",;"><mml:mrow><mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace><mml:msub><mml: